# Template for apps/mc/.env — copy to `apps/mc/.env` and fill in values.
# The real file is gitignored (root .gitignore covers `.env`) so no
# secret material ever lands in version control.
#
# Read by `docker-compose.dev.yml` via Compose's automatic `.env`
# substitution in the apps/mc/ directory. Missing vars default to
# empty strings — every one of these is strictly optional; the dev
# stack boots fine without them and mc_auth drops into graceful mode.
#
# ============================================================================
# Supabase (mc_auth bridge) — optional, only needed to exercise the
# `/link <code>` flow locally against a live Supabase instance.
# ============================================================================
#
# In production the Agones fleet pods read these from:
#   SUPABASE_URL                → http://kong.kilobase.svc.cluster.local:8000
#   SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY   → arc-runners/mc-supabase-credentials.service-role-key
#                                (projected from kilobase/supabase-jwt.service-key
#                                 via external-secrets; see supabase-external-secret.yaml)
#
# Locally you have two reasonable options:
#
# (a) Leave both blank (or omit this file entirely). mc_auth logs a
#     warning on startup and treats every player as Unlinked. Good
#     enough for iterating on the Fabric / Velocity / mod side of
#     things when you don't care about the link flow.
#
# (b) Point at the real kilobase stack via `kubectl port-forward`:
#
#         kubectl port-forward -n kilobase svc/kong 8000:8000
#
#     ...then fill the two vars below. `host.docker.internal` reaches
#     the host's port-forward from inside the mc-fabric container
#     (docker-compose.dev.yml sets host-gateway for Linux support).
#
#     The service-role JWT lives in `kilobase/supabase-jwt.service-key`
#     — grab it with:
#
#         kubectl get secret supabase-jwt -n kilobase \
#             -o jsonpath='{.data.service-key}' | base64 -d
#
SUPABASE_URL=
SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=
